      "title": "Solar Sailing Trajectory Control for Sub-L1 Stationkeeping",
      "abstract": "Solar sails provide unique capabilities for space missions, due to the opportunities f or non - Keplerian orbits provided by significant continuous thrust over the mission life. This paper focuses on a particular example, which takes advantage of the increased warning time of solar flare events afforded by stationing a solar sail spacecraft si gnificantly inside the Earth - Sun L1 equilibrium. In the case of a circular Earth orbit about the sun, it is known that a 2 - dimensional manifold of station keeping equilibria exist in the synodic frame, parameterized by the in -plane and out -of -plane offsets of the station from the Earth -Sun line. Although no expendable fuel is required to maintain such an equilibrium, these equilibria are not stable, and periodic corrections to the nominal sail thrust vector (e.g. with feedback control) are required to main tain station. Since the sail thrust magnitude is a function of the attitude of the sail normal relative to the spacecraft -sun line, the corrective control thrusts derived from attitude changes on the sailcraft are constrained to a 2 -dimensional manifold, raising questions about the controllability of the desired equilibrium. It is shown in this paper that a 10,000 square meter sail with representative reflectance properties is controllable, according to the standard test for linearized dynamics, for a larg e region on the station keeping manifold. However, this result does not imply that sail attitude (thrust correction) angles will be within acceptable limits for particular initial off -equilibrium conditions. A controllability Gramian approach is used to pr ovide quantitative estimates of initial state errors which are correctable to zero within a given time, such that sailcraft attitude adjustments remain within specified limits. This enables early analysis of a mission profile to indicate whether orbit inje ction errors relative to the desired station are correctable. It can also be used to quantify tracking error correctability along non -equilibrium trajectories. Examples of its use in sub -L1 halo trajectory tracking are provided for the case of an eccentric Earth orbit."
